<PageInfo index=false title="Test your microphone"/>

<xtablecenter width=80%>
	<xtrheader>Test your microphone</xtrheader>
	<tr>
		<td>
			<p>
				To the right is an <bold>oscillascope</bold>. As your speak
				into your microphone, you should see:
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>
					The familiar <bold>wiggly oscillascope line in white</bold>.
					As you speak, you will see the lines wiggle, practically
					growing to the full height of the oscillascope.
				</li>
				<p>
					If the lines don't vertically cover most of the oscillascope
					when you speak, then you can either move the microphone
					closer to your mouth, or increase your volume level.
					See below.
				</p>
				<li>
					If the <bold>background turns red</bold> then your
					audio is "clipping", which means that either your microphone
					is too close to your mouth, or you need to reduce
					your record volume. See below.
				</li>
				<li>
					The <bold>blue spikes</bold> on the lower-left corner
					of the oscillascope show that frequencies and harmonics
					the microphone is recording. If you don't know what this
					is (which you probably don't) then ignore it.
				</li>
			</ul>
			
			<p>
				You will probably need to <bold>adjust the record
				level</bold> on your sound card. If the curvy white
				lines touch the top and bottom of the oscillascope,
				or the background of
				the oscillascope turns red, you need
				to <bold>reduce your microphone level</bold>. If
				the curvy white lines aren't very tall when
				you speak, you need
				to <bold>increase your microphone level</bold>.
			</p>
			
			<ol>
				<li>
					Unforunately, sound card manufacturers haven't made
					life easy for us. Each sound card usually comes with
					its own "Volume control" applet, each one different
					than the others. This applet can usually be accessed
					by <bold>double-clicking a small speaker icon
					on your Windows taskbar</bold>, near the clock.
					You may need press the left arrow (&lt;) near the clock
					to show the full list of icons.
				</li>
				<p>
					If you can't find the speaker icon, or double-clicking
					it doens't work, then pull up the <bold>Windows
					control panel</bold>, click on <bold>"Sounds, speech,
					and Audio Devices"</bold>. Then, click on <bold>"Adjust
					the system volume"</bold>. Select
					the <bold>"Audio"</bold> tab. Click on
					the <bold>"Volume"</bold> button in the
					"Sound recording" section.
				</p>
				
				<li>
					Once you have the volume control up, you need to find the <bold>microphone
					recording controls level adjustment</bold>, or whatever
					it's called on your sound card. This is different for every sound card.
					The process I'll describe is for the standard Windows volume
					control, which you may or may not have.
				</li>
				
				<li>
					Under the "Options" menu, select <bold>Properties</bold>.
				</li>
				
				<li>
					The "Properties" dialog will appear. Select
					the <bold>Recording</bold> button in the "Adjust volume for"
					section. Then, press <bold>OK</bold>.
				</li>
				
				<li>
					The volume control will change to display different sliders.
					Find the one labelled "Microphone" and make sure
					that <bold>Select</bold> is checked (if it isn't already). This
					causes your sound card to record from your microphone,
					and not your line-in or CD.
				</li>
				<li>
					<bold>Adjust</bold> the vertical volume slider up/down. You
					should notice an effect on the curvy white lines in the
					oscillascope as you speak. If you <bold>do not</bold> detect
					any differences then you might be adjusting the volume
					for the wrong sound card/device.
				</li>
				<li>
					If you can't adjust the volume loud enough or quiet enough,
					you may need to check out some advanced controls...
				</li>
				<li>
					To see the advanced controls, display the "Options" menu
					and select the <bold>Advanced controls</bold> menu if
					it's not already displayed.
				</li>
				<li>
					If an <bold>Advanced</bold> button appears underneath the
					microphone slider, then <bold>press it</bold>.
				</li>
				<li>
					The "Advanced" dialog will appear; it's content vary from
					sound card to sound card. If you find an option
					like <bold>20 dB boost</bold> then try checking or unchecking
					it. If not, try playing with the other controls to see
					if they work.
				</li>
			</ol>
			
			<p>
				By this point, <bold>you should have adjusted your microphone
				volume control</bold> so that it's high enough that
				the oscillascope's white curvy lines use up most of area (vertically),
				but not so much that they touch the top/bottm of the
				oscillascope and the background turns red.
			</p>
			
			<p>
				If you are having problems with this, see below.
			</p>
		</td>
		<td>
			<p align=center>
				<image width=304 height=204 border=2 hbitmap=<<<HBITMAP>>> name=image/>
			</p>
			
			<xChoiceButton style=righttriangle href="p:1020">
				<bold>Next</bold><br/>
				Press this <bold>after</bold> you have properly
				adjusted the volume control.
				The next page will let you listen to some of your
				recordings to make sure they're clear.
			</xChoiceButton>
			
			<xbr/>
			
			<table width=100%>
				<tr>
					<td><align align=center>
						<br/><image bmpresource=815/><br/>
						Good volume level
					</align></td>
					<td><align align=center>
						<br/><image bmpresource=813/><br/>
						Too loud
					</align></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><align align=center>
						<br/><image bmpresource=814/><br/>
						Not hearing anything
					</align></td>
					<td><align align=center>
						<br/><image bmpresource=812/><br/>
