					</align></td>
				</tr>
			</table>
		</td>
		
	</tr>
</xtablecenter>


<xtablecenter width=80%>
	<xtrheader>What to do if it doesn't work...</xtrheader>
	<tr><td>
		This section may help you if you're having problems.
	</td></tr>
	<xtrheader>The white line doesn't wiggle when I speak...</xtrheader>
	<tr><td>
		<p>
			If the white line has no response whatsoever when you speak, then
			try the following:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				You may have <bold>forgotten to plug in your microphone, or may have plugged
				it into the wrong hole.</bold>
			</li>
			<li>
				<bold>The sound card may be recording from the CD or line-in.</bold> Most
				sound cards have the ability to record direct from CD or from the line-in
				port. See above for directions on how to tell your sound card to
				record from the microphone.
			</li>
			<li>
				<bold>MIF may be recording from the wrong sound card.</bold> If you have
				more than one sound card/device, or sometimes even a MODEM, MIF could
				be recording from the wrong one.
			</li>
			<p>
				To change the sound card, run the Windows <bold>control
				panel</bold>, go to <bold>"Sounds, Speech, and Audio
				Devices"</bold>. Click on <bold>"Sounds and audio
				devices"</bold>. Select the <bold>"Audio"</bold> tab.
				Under the "Sound recording" section, set
				the <bold>Default device</bold> to your sound card.
				Press <bold>"Back"</bold> on this page and try again.
			</p>
			<li>
				<bold>The microphone may be incompatible with your sound card.</bold> There
				are different types of microphones. Some microphones don't work with
				computer sound cards. (If you purchased your microphone at
				a computer store, it probably works. If your microphone was purchased
				at a music store, it may not work.)
			</li>
			<li>
				You microphone <bold>may have a small mute/silence switch on it.</bold>
			</li>
			<li>
				<bold>The microphone may be broken.</bold> This is always a possibility.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</td></tr>
	
	<xtrheader>The white line wiggles, but is very flat (vertically)...</xtrheader>
	<tr><td>
		<p>
			This sounds like your volume setting for the sound card is too
			loud/quiet. Try the following:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<bold>Adjust the recording volume control</bold> as described at the
				top of this page. You might also try <bold>moving
				the microphone</bold> closer or futher away.
			</li>
			<li>
				If you can't increase the volume enough, <bold>your microphone may
				not produce enough volume for your sound card</bold>. To solve this,
				you either need to move the microphone closer, buy a new microphone,
				or buy a new sound card. If you're an audio engineer you can run
				the microphone through a pre-amp.
			</li>
			<li>
				You microphone <bold>may have a small volume-control knob or
				slider on it.</bold>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</td></tr>

	<xtrheader>My computer (the software) crashes/hangs when I record...</xtrheader>
	<tr><td>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<bold>Try downloading the latest drivers</bold> from your sound card
				manufacturer.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</td></tr>
</xtablecenter>
